This interface provides a way of decoupling task submission from the
mechanics of how each task will be run, including details of thread
use, scheduling, etc.  An  is normally used
instead of explicitly creating threads.


However, the  interface does not strictly
require that execution be asynchronous. In the simplest case, an
executor can run the submitted task immediately in the caller's
thread:


class DirectExecutor : IExecutor {
	public void Execute(IRunnable r) {
		r.Run();
	}
    public void Execute(Action task) {
        task();
    }
}



More typically, tasks are executed in some thread other
than the caller's thread.  The executor below spawns a new thread
for each task.


class ThreadPerTaskExecutor : IExecutor {
	public void Execute(IRunnable r) {
		new Thread(new ThreadStart(r.Run)).Start();
	}
    public void Execute(Action task) {
        new Thread(new ThreadStart(task)).Start();
    }
}


Many  implementations impose some sort of
limitation on how and when tasks are scheduled. 


The  implementations provided in this package
implement , which is a more extensive
interface.  The  class provides an
extensible thread pool implementation. The  class
provides convenient factory methods for these Executors.

remarks.example:
Usage Examples.


Suppose you have a set of solvers for a certain problem, each 
returning a value of some type Result, and would like to run 
them concurrently, processing the results of each of them that
return a non-null value, in some method Use(Result r). You
could write this as:


  void Solve(IExecutor e,
             ICollection<ICallable<Result>> solvers)
  {
      ICompletionService<Result> ecs
          = new ExecutorCompletionService<Result>(e);
      foreach (ICallable<Result> s in solvers)
          ecs.Submit(s);
      int n = solvers.size();
      for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
          Result r = ecs.Take().GetResult();
          if (r != null) Use(r);
      }
  }



Suppose instead that you would like to use the first non-null result
of the set of tasks, ignoring any that encounter exceptions,
and cancelling all other tasks when the first one is ready:


  void Solve(IExecutor e,
             ICollection<ICallable<Result>> solvers)
  {
      ICompletionService<Result> ecs
          = new ExecutorCompletionService<Result>(e);
      int n = solvers.Count;
      IList<IFuture<Result>> futures
          = new List<IFuture<Result>>(n);
      Result result = null;
      try {
          foreach (ICallable<Result> s in solvers)
              futures.Add(ecs.Submit(s));
          for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
              try {
                  Result r = ecs.Take().GetResult();
                  if (r != null) {
                      result = r;
                      break;
                  }
              } catch (ExecutionException ignore) {}
          }
      }
      finally {
          for (IFuture<Result> f : futures)
              f.Cancel(true);
      }

      if (result != null)
          Use(result);
  }

